From: stopless-java-gc <noreply@anthropic.com>
Subject: [PATCH 0034/N] Modules.gmk: bsd target borrows macosx/classes

Java class compilation for `bsd` target fails with hundreds of
"cannot find symbol" errors because OpenJDK's tree has no
`src/java.base/bsd/classes/` directory — the BSD-derived NIO
providers (`BsdFileSystemProvider`, `KQueueSelectorProvider`,
`DefaultFileSystemProvider`, etc.) live under `macosx/classes/`.

`make/common/Modules.gmk` selects per-module source dirs as:
  $(OPENJDK_TARGET_OS)/classes        — e.g., bsd/classes (missing)
  $(OPENJDK_TARGET_OS_TYPE)/classes   — unix/classes (lacks providers)
  share/classes

Add a `bsd → macosx/classes` rule. The macosx tree is largely
BSD-portable (the surface API is `BsdNativeDispatcher`,
`KQueueSelectorImpl`, etc.) with a thin MacOSX subclass layer
on top. For Phase 1 the MacOSX-specific classes (UTIFileTypeDetector
etc.) compile cleanly even on CheriBSD since they don't depend on
Apple-only native symbols at compile time.

A cleaner long-term fix is to create a real `src/java.base/bsd/`
directory and split the macosx/classes into bsd-shared + macosx-only.
That's out of scope for Phase 1 (build-only); revisit when the JDK
actually runs on the FVP.

Refs: docs/05_zgc_cheri_collision_report.md §6 (patch 0034)

--- a/make/common/Modules.gmk
+++ b/make/common/Modules.gmk
@@ -88,6 +88,14 @@
 ifneq ($(OPENJDK_TARGET_OS), $(OPENJDK_TARGET_OS_TYPE))
   SRC_SUBDIRS += $(OPENJDK_TARGET_OS_TYPE)/classes
 endif
+# Phase 1: when targeting bsd (CheriBSD), the upstream tree has no bsd/classes
+# directory but macosx/classes contains the BSD-derived NIO providers
+# (BsdFileSystemProvider, KQueueSelectorProvider, etc.) that we need. Pull
+# them in for bsd target so that classes like sun.nio.fs.DefaultFileSystemProvider
+# resolve.
+ifeq ($(OPENJDK_TARGET_OS), bsd)
+  SRC_SUBDIRS += macosx/classes
+endif
 SRC_SUBDIRS += share/classes

 SPEC_SUBDIRS += share/specs
